cs.CR, cs.DS, cs.DB, cs.CY, cs.LG 

This paper proposes a differentially private ORAM protocol, which involves techniques from cryptography, data structures, and privacy. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The paper also discusses the performance and storage overhead of the proposed protocol, which suggests that it could be relevant to the categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DB (Databases). The paper also mentions the use of statistical privacy, which could be relevant to the category of cs.CY (Computers and Society). Finally, the paper uses information theoretic metrics to analyze privacy guarantees, which suggests that it could be relevant to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
